        <article>
          <aside class="js-overview text vertical"  >
  <div class="overview table">
    <h3>How it Works</h3>

    <p>
      Take a tour of the most productive, powerful, and scalable cloud application
      platform, and learn how Heroku structures and handles your app, deploys,
      scaling, and traffic.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Click around the diagram or the tabs above to explore.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>
</aside>
<aside class="js-deploy text" style="display:none">
  <h3>Instant Deployment</h3>

  <p>
    Deploying an app is simple and easy.  No special tools needed, just a plain
    <a href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/git"><code>git push</code></a>. Deployment is instant, whether your app is
    big or small.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/git">Read more about git deployment...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Continuous Deployment</h3>

  <p>
    Easily create testing, staging, and production versions of your
    app and deploy to and between them instantly. The <a class="js-clickable js-relax" href="#">dyno
    manifold</a> insures all parts of your app are updated and bounced
    gracefully, <a href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/http-routing">routing</a> continues seamlessly, and traffic is
    held for data migrations by custom maintenance <a class="js-clickable js-command" href="#">controls</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>Poka-yoke (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poka-yoke">ポカヨケ</a>)</h3>

  <p>
    Move quickly and with confidence: Heroku follows a poka-yoke (mistake-proof)
    <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poka-yoke">design philosophy</a>, including role-based permissions,
    integrity checks during push, and robust release management and rollback <a
    class="js-clickable js-command" href="#">controls</a>.  If in doubt, watch every detail of the deployment
    process in real-time with <a class="js-clickable js-observe" href="#">Logplex</a>.
  </p>
</aside>
<aside class="js-connect text" style="display:none">
  <h3>Add-on Resources</h3>

  <p>
    Instantly provision and integrate third party services with one click.
    Heroku's large catalog of third party add-on services is constantly growing,
    and includes services like databases, caching, monitoring, performance
    management, email, transcoding, search, billing, and many more.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://addons.heroku.com/">Visit Add-ons Catalog...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Per-Deploy Config Variables</h3>

  <p>
    Store credentials to external services like S3 or Twitter in config vars,
    exposed to your app as environment variables. Per-deploy environment
    variables are more secure and provide the flexibility to use different
    end-points for development, staging, and production.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/config-vars">Read more about config vars...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Custom Services</h3>

  <p>
    Roll your own custom service (e.g. MySQL running on Amazon's EC2) just by
    adding its access credentials to your app's <a href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/config-vars">config vars</a>.
    They will be available as environment variables to all <a class="js-clickable js-scale" href="#">dynos</a>.
  </p>
</aside>
<aside class="js-command text" style="display:none">
  <div class="recessed">
    <h3>Control Surfaces</h3>

    <p>
      Heroku provides the following control surfaces for managing your app and its
      operations, all available as a command-line interface (CLI), web console, or
      full REST API.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Deployment and Release Management</h3>

  <p>
    <a href="#" class="js-clickable js-deploy">Deploy</a> code, view and manage a complete audit log of all
    changes, and rollback instantly to any version.
  </p>

  <h3>Add-ons and Config Vars</h3>

  <p>
    Add, remove, upgrade, and downgrade <a class="js-clickable js-connect" href="#">connected resources</a> on
    the fly via add-ons, and manage per-deploy config variables for external
    resources.
  </p>

  <h3>Collaboration</h3>

  <p>
    Manage sharing, deployment, and billing permissions via role-based access
    control.
  </p>

  <h3>Scaling & Process Management</h3>

  <p>
    Independently <a class="js-clickable js-scale" href="#">scale</a> each part of your app, inspect
    individual processes, and run any one-off command or interactive console.
  </p>

  <h3>Routing</h3>

  <p>
    Fine-grained control of DNS, custom domains, SSL, maintenance mode, and
    error handling.
  </p>

  <h3>Logging and Visibility</h3>

  <p>
    Full <a class="js-clickable js-observe" href="#">visibility</a> into your app's operations with real-time
    logging, process status inspection, and an audit trail of all releases.  
  </p>
</aside>
<aside class="js-observe text" style="display:none">
  <div class="recessed">
    <h3>Total Visibility</h3>

    <p>
      Heroku's Logplex provides an unprecedented level of visibility into your
      app's operations, acting as an aggregation point for all logging activity
      across the platform.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Full Logging</h3>

  <p>
    See all logging output from every component of your app and each dyno, and
    output from every piece of the Heroku platform as it deploys your app,
    manages your dynos, and handles HTTP requests.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/logging">Read more about logging...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Process Status</h3>

  <p>
    Inspect the status of all app dynos across the platform. Watch the <a
    href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dyno-manifold">dyno manifold</a> bring dynos up and down and keep them running,
    all in real-time.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/ps">Read more about the ps command...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Advanced Use</h3>

  <p>
    Filter logs by component or platform layer, or tail your logs in real-time,
    all from the command line.
  </p>

  <h3>Extensible</h3>

  <p>
    Connected resources can channel logs into your log stream (such as system
    logs from the Heroku PostgreSQL add-on), and syslog drains can send your
    logs to an external service or custom log archival location.
  </p>
</aside>
<aside class="js-scale text" style="display:none">
  <div class="recessed">
    <h3>Scaling</h3>

    <p>
      With full <a class="js-clickable js-command" href="#">control</a>, instant spin-up, infinite capacity, and
      independent scaling for each component of your app, Heroku offers the most
      advanced and powerful web scaling platform to date.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Dynos</h3>

  <p>
    Forget servers, instances, and VMs. Focus on processes. Dynos are <a
    href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dyno-isolation">fully-isolated</a>, <a href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/erosion-resistance">erosion-resistent</a> processes
    running on and kept alive by the <a href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dyno-manifold">dyno manifold</a>. Dynos
    receive web requests from routing, connect to app <a class="js-clickable js-connect" href="#">resources</a>
    via environment variables, and write output to <a class="js-clickable js-observe" href="#">Logplex</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dynos">Read more about dynos...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Process Types</h3>

  <p>

    Define your app's parts with a <a href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/procfile">Procfile</a>, then scale the
    dynos for each component independently (web, workers, and more). This
    extremely powerful process model allows apps to scale without constant
    re-architecting.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/process-model">Read more about the process model...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Routing</h3>

  <p>
    Incoming web traffic is automatically routed to web dynos, with intelligent
    distribution of load instantly as you scale. Rich APIs allow fine-grained
    control of DNS, domains, SSL, maintenance, and error handling.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/http-routing">Read more about routing...</a>
  </p>
</aside>
<aside class="js-relax text" style="display:none">
  <div class="recessed">
    <h3>Relax</h3>

    <p>
      Once you've <a class="js-clickable js-deploy" href="#">pushed code</a> and <a class="js-clickable js-scale" href="#">scaled</a> your
      dynos, Heroku takes full responsibility for your app's health. Entrust the <a
      href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dyno-manifold">dyno manifold</a> to ensure your app is running the right number
      of healthy dynos at all times.
    </p>

    <p class="more">
      <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dyno-manifold">Read more about the dyno manifold...</a>
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Isolation</h3>

  <p class="more">
    Each dyno is completely isolated (using <a href="http://lxc.sourceforge.net/">LXC</a> OS-level
    virtualization), providing a secure and performance-consistent environment.
    Dynos can't run out of memory or be adversely affected by other processes,
    including one-off administrative processes.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/dyno-isolation">Read more about dyno isolation...</a>
  </p>

  <h3>Erosion-resistance</h3>

  <p>
    Heroku takes care of security issues, OS patching, library updates, shifting
    dependencies, crashing processes, memory leaks, and even hardware failure,
    keeping your dynos running throughout.  Web apps are continually subject to
    extreme erosive forces, but Heroku's architecture provides strong
    resistance, keeping apps running unattended literally for years.
  </p>

  <p class="more">
    <a class="button" href="http://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/erosion-resistance">Read more about erosion-resistance...</a>
  </p>
</aside>


